notesStmt.note: Zacour-Hirsch treats full incipit as title and attributes the manuscript to Petrus Pandoni, a name for which there is a reference in the entry for Porcellius in Cosenza's Biographical and bibliographical dictionary of the Italian humanists, 1962.
Incipit: Porcelii poetae clarissimi et oratoris ortographia incipit. Lege feliciter. Et si duram mihi provinciam humanissime vir...
Explicit: Quia placuit magis consuetudine conprobari. Porcelii poete clarissimi et oratoris ortografia explicit.

msContents.summary: Treatise on the part of grammar dealing with spelling and with the nature and value of letters and their combinations.

msItem.title: Porcelii poetae clarissimi et oratoris Ortographia
msItem.author: Porcellius, Johannes Antonius, ca. 1405-ca. 1485?

supportDesc.extent: 86 leaves : 167 x 117 (92 x 70) mm. bound to 167 x 120 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, 86; [1-86]; modern foliation in pencil, lower right recto.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 17 long lines; ruled in ink.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a humanistic script by a single hand.

decoDesc.decoNote: Illuminated initials in gold, blue, red, and green (f. 3r, f. 4v); rubricated initials, headings, and underlining.

history.provenance: Formerly owned by D. Andreas Parisino, (signature, f. 3r, 83v, 85v).

keywords.term: Latin language--Orthography and spelling--Early works to 1800
